Sapir-Whorf hypothesis
>The Theory of linguistic relativity or Principle of linguistic relativity, the Sapir-Whorf The Sapir-Whorf hypothesis (SWH) is a hypothesis that challenges the position that the real world can be correctly understood in any language, and proposes that language is involved in the formation of the worldview of its speakers. It is a theory advocated by Benjamin Whorf that systematizes the influence of an individual's thinking on the language he or she is able to use. It formed the basis for the work of Whorf and Edward Sapir.
